      <span class="section-label">THE SECOND YOUNG MASTER</span>
      <h1>Chapter 3</h1>

      <div class="story-body">
        <p>When I entered the estate, one of our senior butlers greeted me.</p>
        <p>"Please handle any minor disputes," I told him.</p>
        <p>He bowed.</p>
        <p>"As you wish, my lord."</p>
        <p>I thanked him and headed to my room.</p>
        <p>Tomorrow was another academy day.</p>
        <p>The next morning, I arrived at KST Academy.</p>
        <p>As I entered, my eyes naturally drifted toward the large board displaying the academy structure.</p>
        <p>I remembered my first day here.</p>
        <p>My father had personally explained the system to us.</p>
        <p>Somehow, I had made it to the third year.</p>
        <p>The first year had belonged to House Turney.</p>
        <p>Basic Magic.</p>
        <p>General Sorcery.</p>
        <p>Mana Control.</p>
        <p>The year where most students got stuck.</p>
        <p>The second year focused on specialization.</p>
        <p>Assassination.</p>
        <p>Healing.</p>
        <p>Warfare.</p>
        <p>Diplomacy.</p>
        <p>Magecraft.</p>
        <p>I had survived Professor Dron's classes and cleared the requirements needed to advance.</p>
        <p>Now came the third year.</p>
        <p>State Affairs.</p>
        <p>House Solaris would be taking over our education.</p>
        <p>Politics.</p>
        <p>Bureaucracy.</p>
        <p>Administration.</p>
        <p>Taxation.</p>
        <p>Governance.</p>
        <p>I still wasn't entirely sure why an assassin needed to understand tax collection.</p>
        <p>Then again, House Solaris had built half the institutions in the kingdom.</p>
        <p>There was probably a reason for it.</p>
        <p>I wondered how many students would be joining the third year.</p>
        <p>When my batch entered the academy, there had been far more students.</p>
        <p>Now only thirty remained.</p>
        <p>Two had already reached the fourth year.</p>
        <p>Twelve were still trapped in the first year.</p>
        <p>The rest were scattered between the second and third years.</p>
        <p>The academy was never in a hurry to graduate anyone.</p>
        <p>My eyes moved to the next section.</p>
        <p>Fourth Year.</p>
        <p>Field Application.</p>
        <p>No classrooms.</p>
        <p>No lectures.</p>
        <p>Only missions.</p>
        <p>A healer might spend years attached to an army.</p>
        <p>A diplomat could be sent to negotiate a treaty.</p>
        <p>A warrior could be assigned to clear a monster-infested region.</p>
        <p>An assassin could be sent after a heavily protected target.</p>
        <p>Then came the final year.</p>
        <p>Legacy Creation.</p>
        <p>An assassin had to create a team.</p>
        <p>A healer had to establish a clinic.</p>
        <p>A warrior had to raise a troop.</p>
        <p>A diplomat had to create an alliance or administrative system.</p>
        <p>Everything would be judged by a board.</p>
        <p>I stared at the structure for a few moments.</p>
        <p>Third year.</p>
        <p>Three more years remained.</p>
        <p>I went inside the classroom and took my seat.</p>
        <p>A few minutes later, our professor entered.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron Solaris.</p>
        <p>Like every member of House Solaris, he carried himself with a calm dignity that was difficult to describe.</p>
        <p>He greeted us politely.</p>
        <p>With respect.</p>
        <p>With courtesy.</p>
        <p>It was something we had never received from any of our previous instructors.</p>
        <p>Professor Dron would torture us.</p>
        <p>Professor Isaac would try to kill us.</p>
        <p>House Solaris, however, taught differently.</p>
        <p>There was something about them.</p>
        <p>A quiet confidence.</p>
        <p>The kind that didn't need to prove itself.</p>
        <p>Once everyone was seated, Professor Ron began the lesson.</p>
        <p>The first topic was the structure of our kingdom.</p>
        <p>He explained how authority flowed through the state.</p>
        <p>At the top stood House Globus.</p>
        <p>The royal family.</p>
        <p>The king possessed the authority to question, modify, or overturn any law imposed by a noble house, government office, or regional administration.</p>
        <p>However, that power was rarely used recklessly.</p>
        <p>The strength of the kingdom came from the balance maintained between the Crown, the Great Houses, and the bureaucracy established through the Solaris Decree.</p>
        <p>For the next few days, each lesson focused on a different subject.</p>
        <p>Our neighboring kingdoms.</p>
        <p>Our allies.</p>
        <p>Trade routes.</p>
        <p>Military strengths.</p>
        <p>Economic weaknesses.</p>
        <p>Border disputes.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron was extremely thorough.</p>
        <p>Every lecture was supported by reports, historical examples, and records collected over generations.</p>
        <p>Then one day, the topic shifted to House Whitlock.</p>
        <p>The room immediately became more attentive.</p>
        <p>Recent events had ensured everyone knew the name.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron stood before the board and spoke.</p>
        <p>"For over a thousand years, House Whitlock has supported the Crown."</p>
        <p>He then began listing examples.</p>
        <p>During famines, they opened their grain reserves.</p>
        <p>During rebellions, they supplied soldiers.</p>
        <p>During economic crises, they funded reconstruction efforts.</p>
        <p>Then he reached the Eastern War against the Kingdom of Fera.</p>
        <p>Even I had heard stories about that battle.</p>
        <p>"The Crown Prince's army was surrounded," Professor Ron explained.</p>
        <p>"The enemy had successfully pinned down the royal forces."</p>
        <p>At that point, defeat had seemed inevitable.</p>
        <p>Then Henry Whitlock acted.</p>
        <p>Without waiting for orders, he redirected his cavalry toward the enemy advance.</p>
        <p>The purpose was simple.</p>
        <p>Buy time.</p>
        <p>Allow the Crown Prince to escape.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron paused before continuing.</p>
        <p>"Henry Whitlock and twenty-five riders engaged the enemy Royal Commander and a force of nearly one thousand soldiers."</p>
        <p>The classroom became silent.</p>
        <p>Everyone knew what that meant.</p>
        <p>It was a suicide charge.</p>
        <p>"He held them for three hours."</p>
        <p>Several students looked stunned.</p>
        <p>Three hours.</p>
        <p>Against impossible odds.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron nodded.</p>
        <p>"The Crown Prince survived."</p>
        <p>No further explanation was needed.</p>
        <p>The sacrifice had become one of the most famous acts of loyalty in the kingdom's history.</p>
        <p>Looking back on the current crisis, I understood why the royal family was doing everything possible to help House Whitlock.</p>
        <p>After that, the lesson shifted to another topic.</p>
        <p>The different species living within our kingdom.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron explained that things had not always been peaceful.</p>
        <p>In the distant past, many intelligent races had been treated little better than animals simply because they were different.</p>
        <p>Beastkin.</p>
        <p>Forest-born races.</p>
        <p>Several magical species.</p>
        <p>Many had been denied rights entirely.</p>
        <p>That changed with the Solaris Decree.</p>
        <p>House Solaris pushed for reforms that recognized all intelligent citizens under the law.</p>
        <p>The changes were controversial at the time.</p>
        <p>Today, they were considered normal.</p>
        <p>Many students sitting in the academy itself belonged to races that would once have been excluded from education altogether.</p>
        <p>By the end of the week, we had learned more about the kingdom than I had in years of growing up within it.</p>
        <p>The strengths of each region.</p>
        <p>The weaknesses of each province.</p>
        <p>The cultures.</p>
        <p>The trade networks.</p>
        <p>The military structures.</p>
        <p>Looking at the Whitlock situation, I was beginning to understand why House Solaris taught the third year.</p>
        <p>Apparently, running a kingdom was far more complicated than killing people.</p>
        <p>And the lessons weren't limited to politics and administration.</p>
        <p>Sometimes the hardest question wasn't how to kill someone.</p>
        <p>It was whether they should be killed at all.</p>
        <p>A corrupt but brilliant general standing on the eve of a war was a perfect example.</p>
        <p>Removing him might be morally correct.</p>
        <p>It might also cost thousands of soldiers their lives.</p>
        <p>Likewise, sparing an honest but incompetent leader could be just as disastrous.</p>
        <p>Good intentions rarely saved kingdoms.</p>
        <p>Competence did.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron constantly forced us to look beyond simple answers.</p>
        <p>Every situation had consequences.</p>
        <p>Every decision created new problems.</p>
        <p>And every solution came with a cost.</p>
        <p>Over time, we became much better at assessing situations.</p>
        <p>We learned how to identify signs of rebellion.</p>
        <p>How to recognize corruption.</p>
        <p>How to report suspicious activity to the Solaris Board.</p>
        <p>How to determine whether a noble house was violating kingdom laws or merely exploiting loopholes.</p>
        <p>We also spent considerable time studying social structures and etiquette.</p>
        <p>A surprising amount of diplomacy involved knowing who should speak first, who should remain silent, and which customs could accidentally start an argument.</p>
        <p>Then came languages.</p>
        <p>We learned three in total.</p>
        <p>The first was Elven.</p>
        <p>Most of the eastern kingdoms were Elven nations, and many historians believed the last war had escalated because of misunderstandings and poor communication between diplomats.</p>
        <p>The second language belonged to the Water Folk.</p>
        <p>Although many of them lived within eastern territories, their speech differed noticeably from both human and elven languages.</p>
        <p>Fortunately, it was relatively easy to learn.</p>
        <p>The third focused less on words and more on people.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron called it the language of crowds.</p>
        <p>What do you say to a hungry crowd?</p>
        <p>What do you say to an angry crowd?</p>
        <p>What do you say when people are frightened?</p>
        <p>What do you say when they have already lost hope?</p>
        <p>Those lessons surprised me the most.</p>
        <p>Before joining House Solaris classes, I had always viewed kingdoms through the actions of nobles, soldiers, and powerful mages.</p>
        <p>Professor Ron disagreed.</p>
        <p>According to him, a kingdom's greatest strength was neither its army nor its noble houses.</p>
        <p>It was its people.</p>
        <p>The farmers who produced food.</p>
        <p>The merchants who moved goods.</p>
        <p>The craftsmen who built roads and cities.</p>
        <p>The ordinary citizens who paid taxes and kept the kingdom functioning.</p>
        <p>House Solaris believed that the common people were just as important as any of the Twenty-Five Great Houses.</p>
        <p>And after a few months of their lectures, I was beginning to understand why.</p>
        
  <p>The third year wasn't limited to academy lessons.</p>

  <p>Whenever I returned to the estate, work was waiting for me.</p>

  <p>As acting head in my father's absence, I had to review reports, sign decisions, settle disputes between minor nobles, and occasionally authorize assassin deployments when problems required a more direct solution.</p>

  <p>Most issues were routine.</p>

  <p>Land disputes.</p>

  <p>Trade disagreements.</p>

  <p>Tax complaints.</p>

  <p>The kind of problems every territory dealt with.</p>

  <p>Then there was the farmer.</p>

  <p>For an entire week, he came to the estate every single day.</p>

  <p>The servants would meet him at the gate and ask for his problem.</p>

  <p>Every time he gave the same answer.</p>

  <p>"I want to speak with the head of House Kasper."</p>

  <p>Nothing more.</p>

  <p>Nothing less.</p>

  <p>After seven days, I finally noticed him myself.</p>

  <p>The man looked exhausted.</p>

  <p>His clothes were worn.</p>

  <p>His hands were rough from years of labor.</p>

  <p>I walked over.</p>

  <p>"What is it?"</p>

  <p>The farmer immediately bowed.</p>

  <p>"I wish to speak with the head of House Kasper."</p>

  <p>"I am currently acting as the head."</p>

  <p>The farmer looked surprised for a moment before nodding.</p>

  <p>Then he finally explained.</p>

  <p>"There is a young girl in the city brothel."</p>

  <p>I looked at him.</p>

  <p>"So?"</p>

  <p>The farmer hesitated.</p>

  <p>"She is only eleven."</p>

  <p>For a moment, I simply stared at him.</p>

  <p>I didn't immediately understand why he had come to us.</p>

  <p>Then the butler quietly stepped beside me.</p>

  <p>"Young Master," he whispered, "your father dislikes children being used in such work."</p>

  <p>I frowned.</p>

  <p>"Is it illegal?"</p>

  <p>"No."</p>

  <p>That answer didn't surprise me.</p>

  <p>The butler continued.</p>

  <p>"If someone legally sold the child, the owner may use them as they see fit."</p>

  <p>I felt my expression darken.</p>

  <p>The butler remained calm.</p>

  <p>"As long as the child receives food, shelter, medical care, and is not severely harmed, the law allows it."</p>

  <p>"So officially we can't do anything?"</p>

  <p>The butler nodded.</p>

  <p>"Officially, no."</p>

  <p>I thought for a few moments.</p>

  <p>Then I asked,</p>

  <p>"What would Father have done?"</p>

  <p>The butler didn't even need to think.</p>

  <p>"He would have bought her."</p>

  <p>I blinked.</p>

  <p>"What?"</p>

  <p>"He would purchase the child."</p>

  <p>The butler's expression remained completely neutral.</p>

  <p>"Then place her in the servant quarters and arrange for her to be raised there."</p>

  <p>Apparently this wasn't the first time.</p>

  <p>"That's what he did with me."</p>

  <p>I turned toward him.</p>

  <p>For the first time since I had known the man, he looked slightly uncomfortable.</p>

  <p>"You?"</p>

  <p>The butler nodded.</p>

  <p>"Many years ago."</p>

  <p>I stared at him.</p>

  <p>Suddenly a great many things started making sense.</p>

  <p>The loyalty.</p>

  <p>The dedication.</p>

  <p>The way our servants would willingly throw themselves into danger for my father.</p>

  <p>I had always assumed it was because House Kasper treated its staff well.</p>

  <p>Now I realized there was more to it.</p>

  <p>Much more.</p>

  <p>"No wonder," I muttered.</p>

  <p>The butler raised an eyebrow.</p>

  <p>"No wonder our servants are so loyal."</p>

  <p>For the first time all day, the old butler smiled.</p>

  <p>A small smile.</p>

  <p>But a genuine one.</p>

  <p>"Yes, Young Master."</p>
  <p>"I suppose that's one reason."</p>

  <p>I instructed the butler to follow Father's usual practice.</p>

  <p>The girl was purchased and brought to the estate a few days later.</p>

  <p>She looked frightened.</p>

  <p>Thin.</p>

  <p>Dirty.</p>

  <p>Far too young to have the expression she carried.</p>

  <p>The moment she entered my office, she lowered her head.</p>

  <p>I studied her for a few seconds.</p>

  <p>"Do you know why I bought you?"</p>

  <p>She shook her head.</p>

  <p>"No, Young Master."</p>

  <p>"I want to make a deal with you."</p>

  <p>That made her look up.</p>

  <p>A deal was probably the last thing she expected to hear.</p>

  <p>I leaned back in my chair.</p>

  <p>"If you clean the gardens every day and do your assigned work properly, I will set you free in five years."</p>

  <p>Her eyes widened.</p>

  <p>I continued.</p>

  <p>"And when those five years are over, I will give you five gold coins."</p>

  <p>For a moment she simply stared at me.</p>

  <p>Then her face lit up.</p>

  <p>"Really?"</p>

  <p>I nodded.</p>

  <p>"Really."</p>

  <p>"Okay, Young Master."</p>

  <p>The answer came immediately.</p>

  <p>She didn't even try to negotiate.</p>

  <p>Then she hesitated.</p>

  <p>"Master..."</p>

  <p>I raised an eyebrow.</p>

  <p>"Yes?"</p>

  <p>"Can you do me one favor?"</p>

  <p>I couldn't help feeling amused.</p>

  <p>Most children would ask for food.</p>

  <p>Or toys.</p>

  <p>Or better clothes.</p>

  <p>"What favor?"</p>

  <p>"Please kill my mother."</p>
  <p>The room became silent.</p>

<p>Even the servants looked uncomfortable.</p>

<p>I simply waited.</p>

<p>"She is raising another child so she can sell her too."</p>

<p>Her voice remained calm.</p>

<p>Almost emotionless.</p>

<p>"Many of the girls in that brothel are from my family."</p>

<p>I sat quietly for several moments.</p>

<p>Then I asked,</p>

<p>"The other child. How old?"</p>

<p>"Five."</p>

<p>"So she won't be sold for another five years?"</p>

<p>The girl nodded.</p>

<p>I thought for a moment.</p>

<p>Then I shook my head.</p>

<p>"No."</p>

<p>Her expression didn't change.</p>

<p>Perhaps she expected the answer.</p>

<p>I continued.</p>

<p>"Work here for five years."</p>

<p>She listened carefully.</p>

<p>"When those five years are over, if you still want revenge, then go kill her yourself."</p>

<p>For the first time, genuine surprise appeared on her face.</p>

<p>"Or hire someone."</p>

<p>I thought for a moment.</p>

<p>"Two silver coins should be enough for a commoner."</p>

<p>The girl slowly nodded.</p>

<p>As if she was memorizing the plan.</p>

<p>Then she bowed.</p>

<p>"Thank you, Young Master."</p>

<p>Without another word, she followed the servants toward the gardens.</p>

<p>I watched her leave.</p>

<p>The butler stepped forward.</p>

<p>"I'll keep an eye on her."</p>

<p>I nodded.</p>

<p>"Please do."</p>

<p>He followed after her.</p>

<p>Once they were gone, I remained seated.</p>

<p>The girl's reaction had impressed me.</p>

<p>No crying.</p>

<p>No begging.</p>

<p>No hesitation.</p>

<p>Just a clear objective.</p>

<p>Then another thought crossed my mind.</p>

<p>If Father hated children being used in brothels so much...</p>

<p>Why didn't he simply outlaw it?</p>

<p>The answer seemed obvious.</p>

<p>He had enough influence.</p>

<p>The king trusted him.</p>

<p>If House Kasper supported such a law, very few nobles would openly oppose it.</p>

<p>So why hadn't he done it?</p>

<p>I made a mental note to ask him when he returned.</p>

<p>Knowing Father, there was probably a reason.</p>

<p>And knowing politics, it was probably far more complicated than it appeared.</p>

  
